{"title_page": "Thai President Foods", "text_new": "{{Infobox company\n| name             = Thai President Foods PCL\n| logo             = TF Logo.png\n| caption          = \n| type             = [[Public company|Public]]\n| traded_as        = {{SET|TFMAMA}}\n| fate             = \n| predecessor      = \n| successor        = \n| foundation       = {{Start date|1972|4|18}}\n| founder          = \n| defunct          = \n| location_city    = [[Bangkok]]\n| location_country = \n| location         = \n| locations        = \n| area_served      = \n| key_people       = Mr Pipat Paniangvait, CEO<ref>{{cite web|title=Management Team|url=https://www.mama.co.th/en/about-organization|website=Thai President Foods PCL|accessdate=4 January 2018}}</ref>\n| industry         = \n| products         = \n| services         = \n| revenue          = 24.9 billion baht (2019)\n| operating_income = \n| net_income       = 5.14 billion baht (2019)\n| aum              = \n| assets           = \n| equity           = \n| owner            = \n| num_employees    = \n| parent           = \n| divisions        = \n| subsid           = \n| homepage         = {{URL|http://www.mama.co.th/}}\n| footnotes        = \n| intl             = \n}}\n\n'''Thai President Foods PCL''' (TF) ({{lang-th|\u0e1a\u0e23\u0e34\u0e29\u0e31\u0e17 \u0e44\u0e17\u0e22 \u0e40\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e0b\u0e34\u0e40\u0e14\u0e19\u0e17\u0e4c \u0e1f\u0e39\u0e14\u0e2a\u0e4c \u0e08\u0e33\u0e01\u0e31\u0e14}}) is a [[Bangkok]]-based [[List of companies of Thailand|Thai company]] established 18 April 1972. It makes the internationally marketed [[instant noodle]] brand \"MAMA\" ({{lang-th|\u0e21\u0e32\u0e21\u0e48\u0e32}}).<ref name=\"BP-20190205\" /> Thai President Foods is the largest [[instant noodle]] manufacturer in [[Thailand]] as of 2020, with a market share of over 50%.<ref name=\"BP-20200417\">{{cite news |last1=Jitpleecheep |first1=Pitsinee |title=Mama producer bulking up |url=http://www.bangkokpost.com/business/1901815/mama-producer-bulking-up?utm_campaign=enewsletter%20regular&utm_source=enewsletter_alert&utm_medium=Business |accessdate=17 April 2020 |work=Bangkok Post |date=17 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=TPBS/>\n\n== History ==\n[[File:Thai instant noodles for sale- different brands.JPG|thumb|MAMA packages on display for sale.]]\t\nSince 1978, the company's shares have been traded on the [[Stock Exchange of Thailand]] (SET).<ref>[http://www.mama.co.th/Company_EN/History.asp www.mama.co.th] Company > History, retrieved 2009-09-19 {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100620125724/http://www.mama.co.th/Company_EN/History.asp |date=June 20, 2010 }}</ref>\n\t\nAs of 2008, 3,824 people were employed by Thai President Foods<ref>[http://wrightreports.ecnext.com/coms2/reportdesc_COMPANY_C76441810 Wright Reports] Thai President Foods Public Company Limited - Company Profile Snapshot, retrieved 2008-09-19 {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070812072819/http://wrightreports.ecnext.com/coms2/reportdesc_COMPANY_C76441810 |date=August 12, 2007 }}</ref>\n\nIn its ''2014 Annual Report'' TPF declared that two company 10-year targets were to grow total income to 20,000 million [[Thai baht|baht]] and to move to a ratio of 50:50 (domestic sales:export sales) from its present 80:20.<ref name=\"TPF-AR2014\" />{{RP|31}} As of 2015, Thai President Foods is the largest [[instant noodle]] manufacturer in [[Thailand]], with a 53% share of the market.<ref name=TPBS>{{cite news|title=Mama instant noodles sale drops for the first time in 42 years| url=http://englishnews.thaipbs.or.th/mama-instant-noodles-sale-drops-for-the-first-time-in-42-years|accessdate=9 June 2015|work=ThaiPBS|date=2015-06-09}}</ref>\n\nA [[Stock Exchange of Thailand]] (SET) ruling in October 2017 approved the de-listing of [[Security (finance)|securities]] for Thai President Foods PLC (PF)  and President Rice Products (PR) and allowed [[Share (finance)|shares]] of the amalgamated firm to be traded on the SET using the ticker symbol TFMAMA. Under the new shareholding structure, TFMAMA is 25% held by SET-listed Saha Pathana Inter-Holding (SPI), the investment holding firm of Saha Group, 16% by [[Nissin Foods|Nissin Holdings]] and the rest by the Chokwatana, Tatiyakawee, Poonsakudomsin, and Paniengvait families.<ref name=\"BP-20180104\">{{cite news|last1=Jitpleecheep|first1=Pitsinee|title=Making Mama instant everywhere|url=https://www.bangkokpost.com/business/news/1390034/making-mama-instant-everywhere|accessdate=4 January 2018|work=Bangkok Post|date=4 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Facilities==\nThe company has factories in [[Lamphun]], [[Si Racha]], [[Rayong]], and two factories in [[Ratchaburi]] in Thailand.<ref>{{cite web|title=Factory|url=http://www.mama.co.th/en/about_profile.php|website=Thai President Foods PCL|accessdate=9 June 2015}}</ref> Expansion in 2020 will raise instant noodle production from its Thai factories to eight million packages per day.<ref name=\"BP-20200417\" /> In addition to its Thailand factories, Thai President has factories in [[Yangon]], [[Myanmar]]; [[Bangladesh]]; [[Cambodia]]; and [[Hungary]].<ref name=\"TPF-AR2014\" />{{RP|33}} The Hungarian factory's two production lines have a capacity of 4.5 million noodle packs per shift per month. It produces \"Thai Chef\" and \"Asia Gold\" brand noodles for the European market.<ref name=\"TPF-AR2014\" />{{RP|33}}\n\nThe company is building a second Myanmar factory in [[Mandalay]], which will increase its Myanmar production to 400,000 packages per day. The company sees potential for growth in Myanmar as the per capita consumption of packaged noodles is only 11.1 packages per year compared with 49 packages per person in [[Thailand]]. Mama's Myanmar sales in 2018 were 657 million baht, projected to double by 2020.<ref name=\"BP-20190205\" />\n\nThe firm is building a new factory in [[Cambodia]] to replace its existing factory. It expects to produce 80,000 cases of noodles per month there, worth 565 million baht per year in revenue by 2020.<ref name=\"BP-20190205\" />\n\n==Financials==\nThai President's consolidated revenue in 2019 was 24.7 billion baht, up from 22.9 billion baht in 2018. Net profit in 2019 rose to 5.14 billion baht.<ref name=\"BP-20200417\" /><ref name=\"BP-20190205\">{{cite news |last1=Jitpleecheep |first1=Pitsinee |title=Mama bolsters noodle production capacity |url=https://www.bangkokpost.com/business/news/1623094/mama-bolsters-noodle-production-capacity |accessdate=2019-02-05 |work=Bangkok Post |date=2019-02-04}}</ref> Total Thai sales of [[Instant noodle|instant noodles]] of all brands in 2015 was estimated at 15.8 billion [[Thai baht|baht]] compared to 2014's 15.4 billion baht.<ref name=TPBS />\n\nIn 2014, when the political crisis slowed Thailand's economic growth to 0.9% and eventually led to a military coup, the growth of MAMA noodle sales hit a low of one percent. In 2015, when the military government could not propel the country beyond an estimated 2.8% growth, sales of MAMA noodles only grew 0.4%\u2014a 44 year record low.<ref name=\"ST-20160202\">{{cite news|last1=Yee|first1=Tan Hui|title=Thailand's queen of instant noodles takes a hit due to slowing economy|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/asia/se-asia/thailands-queen-of-instant-noodles-takes-a-hit-due-to-slowing-economy|accessdate=2 February 2016|work=Straits Times|date=2016-02-02}}</ref> In spite of lacklustre growth in 2014, profits were 1.7 billion baht.<ref>{{cite web|title=Message from the Board of Directors|url=http://www.mama.co.th/en/about_msg.php|website=Thai President PCL|accessdate=9 June 2015}}</ref> Revenue in 2014 was 12 billion baht.<ref name=TPF-AR2014>{{cite book|title=Annual Report 2014|date=2015|url=http://www.mama.co.th/pdf/annual/AnnualTF2014.pdf|publisher=Thai President Foods|accessdate=9 Jun 2015}}</ref>{{RP|3}} The sales contraction in 2015 reflects the economic slowdown which has affected lower-income earners, the main consumers of instant noodles. Mr Wathit Chokewattana, vice president of the company, said that the growth rate of instant noodles has averaged 5\u20136% per year historically. In 2019 MAMA, traditionally the market leader,<ref name=\"TPF-AR2014\" /> remained on top of the Thai instant noodle market{{RP|29}}, followed by [[Wai Wai (food brand)|Wai Wai]] at 23\u201324% and [[Ajinomoto]]'s Yum Yum at 20\u201321%.<ref name=\"BP-20191219\">{{cite news |last1=Jitpleecheep |first1=Pitsinee |title=Thai Preserved Food sees noodles expand |url=https://www.bangkokpost.com/business/1819249/thai-preserved-food-sees-noodles-expand |accessdate=21 December 2019 |work=Bangkok Post |date=19 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Products==\nThai President's product range<ref name=\"TPF-AR2014\" />{{RP|36}} is:\n\n*Food\n**Instant soups, including \"oriental style instant noodles\". Flavours include pork, Thai [[Tom yum]] shrimp, chicken, vegetarian, Vietnamese [[Pho|Ph\u1edf]] (beef), Thai [[Pad kee mao]], [[Thai curry]] and others. Packed in both individual packs and [[disposable cup]]s.\n**Parboiled rice\n**Baked products\n**[[confectionery]]\n**Wheat flour, dry vegetables, rice noodles, and [[seasoning]]s.\n* Soft drinks\n** Fruit juice\n** herbal juices\n** Dairy products\n\n===Instant noodles===\n[[File:MAMA Tom Yum Shrimp Flavor Instant Noodles.png|thumb|MAMA Tom Yum Shrimp Flavor Instant Noodles]]\n\nThe food company's main products are flavoured instant noodles mainly sold under the MAMA brand<ref name=\"ST-20160202\"/> and other brands such as \"Mamy\", \"Pama\", \"Papa\", \"Sai Keo\" and \"Honghow\" which are distributed worldwide. In 2014, the company had an estimated daily capacity of six million packages.<ref name=\"TPF-AR2014\" />{{RP|35}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of companies of Thailand]]\n*[[List of instant noodle brands]]\n*{{portal-inline|Food}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category}}\n*[http://www.mama.co.th/en/index_main.php Official site (English)]\n*[http://finance.google.com/finance?q=BKK:TF finance.google.com] \u2014 Information about Thai President Foods by [[Google Finance]]\n<!-- http://www.computerwire.com/companies/company/?pid=DBA7EDCC-F6C4-4E4E-AE52-2343CD0E8FCF -->\n*[http://instantnoodles.org/index.html World Instant Noodles Association (WINA)]\n\n{{noodles}}\n\n[[Category:Food and drink companies of Thailand]]\n[[Category:Brand name soups]]\n[[Category:Manufacturing companies based in Bangkok]]\n[[Category:Food and drink companies established in 1972]]\n[[Category:Companies listed on the Stock Exchange of Thailand]]\n[[Category:1972 establishments in Thailand]]\n[[Category:Instant noodle brands]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox company\n| name             = Thai President Foods PCL\n| logo             = TF Logo.png\n| caption          = \n| type             = [[Public company|Public]]\n| traded_as        = {{SET|TFMAMA}}\n| fate             = \n| predecessor      = \n| successor        = \n| foundation       = {{Start date|1972|4|18}}\n| founder          = \n| defunct          = \n| location_city    = [[Bangkok]]\n| location_country = \n| location         = \n| locations        = \n| area_served      = \n| key_people       = Mr Pipat Paniangvait, CEO<ref>{{cite web|title=Management Team|url=https://www.mama.co.th/en/about-organization|website=Thai President Foods PCL|accessdate=4 January 2018}}</ref>\n| industry         = \n| products         = \n| services         = \n| revenue          = 24.9 billion baht (2019)\n| operating_income = \n| net_income       = 5.14 billion baht (2019)\n| aum              = \n| assets           = \n| equity           = \n| owner            = \n| num_employees    = \n| parent           = \n| divisions        = \n| subsid           = \n| homepage         = {{URL|http://www.mama.co.th/}}\n| footnotes        = \n| intl             = \n}}\n\n'''Thai President Foods PCL''' (TF) ({{lang-th|\u0e1a\u0e23\u0e34\u0e29\u0e31\u0e17 \u0e44\u0e17\u0e22 \u0e40\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e0b\u0e34\u0e40\u0e14\u0e19\u0e17\u0e4c \u0e1f\u0e39\u0e14\u0e2a\u0e4c \u0e08\u0e33\u0e01\u0e31\u0e14}}) is a [[Bangkok]]-based [[List of companies of Thailand|Thai company]] established 18 April 1972. It makes the internationally marketed [[instant noodle]] brand \"MAMA\" ({{lang-th|\u0e21\u0e32\u0e21\u0e48\u0e32}}).<ref name=\"BP-20190205\" /> Thai President Foods is the largest [[instant noodle]] manufacturer in [[Thailand]] as of 2020, with a market share of over 50%.<ref name=\"BP-20200417\">{{cite news |last1=Jitpleecheep |first1=Pitsinee |title=Mama producer bulking up |url=http://www.bangkokpost.com/business/1901815/mama-producer-bulking-up?utm_campaign=enewsletter%20regular&utm_source=enewsletter_alert&utm_medium=Business |accessdate=17 April 2020 |work=Bangkok Post |date=17 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=TPBS/>\n\n== History ==\n[[File:Thai instant noodles for sale- different brands.JPG|thumb|MAMA packages on display for sale.]]\t\nSince 1978, the company's shares have been traded on the [[Stock Exchange of Thailand]] (SET).<ref>[http://www.mama.co.th/Company_EN/History.asp www.mama.co.th] Company > History, retrieved 2009-09-19 {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100620125724/http://www.mama.co.th/Company_EN/History.asp |date=June 20, 2010 }}</ref>\n\t\nAs of 2008, 3,824 people were employed by Thai President Foods<ref>[http://wrightreports.ecnext.com/coms2/reportdesc_COMPANY_C76441810 Wright Reports] Thai President Foods Public Company Limited - Company Profile Snapshot, retrieved 2008-09-19 {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070812072819/http://wrightreports.ecnext.com/coms2/reportdesc_COMPANY_C76441810 |date=August 12, 2007 }}</ref>\n\nIn its ''2014 Annual Report'' TPF declared that two company 10-year targets were to grow total income to 20,000 million [[Thai baht|baht]] and to move to a ratio of 50:50 (domestic sales:export sales) from its present 80:20.<ref name=\"TPF-AR2014\" />{{RP|31}} As of 2015, Thai President Foods is the largest [[instant noodle]] manufacturer in [[Thailand]], with a 53% share of the market.<ref name=TPBS>{{cite news|title=Mama instant noodles sale drops for the first time in 42 years| url=http://englishnews.thaipbs.or.th/mama-instant-noodles-sale-drops-for-the-first-time-in-42-years|accessdate=9 June 2015|work=ThaiPBS|date=2015-06-09}}</ref>\n\nA [[Stock Exchange of Thailand]] (SET) ruling in October 2017 approved the de-listing of [[Security (finance)|securities]] for Thai President Foods PLC (PF)  and President Rice Products (PR) and allowed [[Share (finance)|shares]] of the amalgamated firm to be traded on the SET using the ticker symbol TFMAMA. Under the new shareholding structure, TFMAMA is 25% held by SET-listed Saha Pathana Inter-Holding (SPI), the investment holding firm of Saha Group, 16% by [[Nissin Foods|Nissin Holdings]] and the rest by the Chokwatana, Tatiyakawee, Poonsakudomsin, and Paniengvait families.<ref name=\"BP-20180104\">{{cite news|last1=Jitpleecheep|first1=Pitsinee|title=Making Mama instant everywhere|url=https://www.bangkokpost.com/business/news/1390034/making-mama-instant-everywhere|accessdate=4 January 2018|work=Bangkok Post|date=4 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Facilities==\nThe company has factories in [[Lamphun]], [[Si Racha]], [[Rayong]], and two factories in [[Ratchaburi]] in Thailand.<ref>{{cite web|title=Factory|url=http://www.mama.co.th/en/about_profile.php|website=Thai President Foods PCL|accessdate=9 June 2015}}</ref> Expansion in 2020 will raise instant noodle production from its Thai factories to eight million packages per day.<ref name=\"BP-20200417\" /> In addition to its Thailand factories, Thai President has factories in [[Yangon]], [[Myanmar]]; [[Bangladesh]]; [[Cambodia]]; and [[Hungary]].<ref name=\"TPF-AR2014\" />{{RP|33}} The Hungarian factory's two production lines have a capacity of 4.5 million noodle packs per shift per month. It produces \"Thai Chef\" and \"Asia Gold\" brand noodles for the European market.<ref name=\"TPF-AR2014\" />{{RP|33}}\n\nThe company is building a second Myanmar factory in [[Mandalay]], which will increase its Myanmar production to 400,000 packages per day. The company sees potential for growth in Myanmar as the per capita consumption of packaged noodles is only 11.1 packages per year compared with 49 packages per person in [[Thailand]]. Mama's Myanmar sales in 2018 were 657 million baht, projected to double by 2020.<ref name=\"BP-20190205\" />\n\nThe firm is building a new factory in [[Cambodia]] to replace its existing factory. It expects to produce 80,000 cases of noodles per month there, worth 565 million baht per year in revenue by 2020.<ref name=\"BP-20190205\" />\n\n==Financials==\nTotal Thai sales of [[Instant noodle|instant noodles]] of all brands in 2015 was estimated at 15.8 billion [[Thai baht|baht]] compared to 2014's 15.4 billion baht.<ref name=TPBS />\n\nIn 2014, when the political crisis slowed Thailand's economic growth to 0.9% and eventually led to a military coup, the growth of MAMA noodle sales hit a low of 1%. In 2015, when the military government could not propel the country beyond an estimated 2.8% growth, sales of MAMA noodles only grew 0.4%\u2014a 44 year record low.<ref name=\"ST-20160202\">{{cite news|last1=Yee|first1=Tan Hui|title=Thailand's queen of instant noodles takes a hit due to slowing economy|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/asia/se-asia/thailands-queen-of-instant-noodles-takes-a-hit-due-to-slowing-economy|accessdate=2 February 2016|work=Straits Times|date=2016-02-02}}</ref> In spite of lacklustre growth in 2014, profits were 1.7 billion baht.<ref>{{cite web|title=Message from the Board of Directors|url=http://www.mama.co.th/en/about_msg.php|website=Thai President PCL|accessdate=9 June 2015}}</ref> Revenue in 2014 was 12 billion baht.<ref name=TPF-AR2014>{{cite book|title=Annual Report 2014|date=2015|url=http://www.mama.co.th/pdf/annual/AnnualTF2014.pdf|publisher=Thai President Foods|accessdate=9 Jun 2015}}</ref>{{RP|3}} The sales contraction in 2015 reflects the economic slowdown which has affected lower-income earners, the main consumers of instant noodles. Mr Wathit Chokewattana, vice president of the company, said that the growth rate of instant noodles has averaged 5\u20136% per year historically. In 2019 MAMA, traditionally the market leader,<ref name=\"TPF-AR2014\" /> remained on top of the Thai instant noodle market{{RP|29}}, followed by [[Wai Wai (food brand)|Wai Wai]] at 23\u201324% and [[Ajinomoto]]'s Yum Yum at 20\u201321%.<ref name=\"BP-20191219\">{{cite news |last1=Jitpleecheep |first1=Pitsinee |title=Thai Preserved Food sees noodles expand |url=https://www.bangkokpost.com/business/1819249/thai-preserved-food-sees-noodles-expand |accessdate=21 December 2019 |work=Bangkok Post |date=19 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nThai President's consolidated revenue in 2019 was 24.7 billion baht, up from 22.9 billion baht in 2018. Net profit in 2019 rose to 5.14 billion baht.<ref name=\"BP-20200417\" /><ref name=\"BP-20190205\">{{cite news |last1=Jitpleecheep |first1=Pitsinee |title=Mama bolsters noodle production capacity |url=https://www.bangkokpost.com/business/news/1623094/mama-bolsters-noodle-production-capacity |accessdate=2019-02-05 |work=Bangkok Post |date=2019-02-04}}</ref>\n\n==Products==\nThai President's product range<ref name=\"TPF-AR2014\" />{{RP|36}} is:\n\n*Food\n**Instant soups, including \"oriental style instant noodles\". Flavours include pork, Thai [[Tom yum]] shrimp, chicken, vegetarian, Vietnamese [[Pho|Ph\u1edf]] (beef), Thai [[Pad kee mao]], [[Thai curry]] and others. Packed in both individual packs and [[disposable cup]]s.\n**Parboiled rice\n**Baked products\n**[[confectionery]]\n**Wheat flour, dry vegetables, rice noodles, and [[seasoning]]s.\n* Soft drinks\n** Fruit juice\n** herbal juices\n** Dairy products\n\n===Instant noodles===\n[[File:MAMA Tom Yum Shrimp Flavor Instant Noodles.png|thumb|MAMA Tom Yum Shrimp Flavor Instant Noodles]]\n\nThe food company's main products are flavoured instant noodles mainly sold under the MAMA brand<ref name=\"ST-20160202\"/> and other brands such as \"Mamy\", \"Pama\", \"Papa\", \"Sai Keo\" and \"Honghow\" which are distributed worldwide. In 2014, the company had an estimated daily capacity of six million packages.<ref name=\"TPF-AR2014\" />{{RP|35}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of companies of Thailand]]\n*[[List of instant noodle brands]]\n*{{portal-inline|Food}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category}}\n*[http://www.mama.co.th/en/index_main.php Official site (English)]\n*[http://finance.google.com/finance?q=BKK:TF finance.google.com] \u2014 Information about Thai President Foods by [[Google Finance]]\n<!-- http://www.computerwire.com/companies/company/?pid=DBA7EDCC-F6C4-4E4E-AE52-2343CD0E8FCF -->\n*[http://instantnoodles.org/index.html World Instant Noodles Association (WINA)]\n\n{{noodles}}\n\n[[Category:Food and drink companies of Thailand]]\n[[Category:Brand name soups]]\n[[Category:Manufacturing companies based in Bangkok]]\n[[Category:Food and drink companies established in 1972]]\n[[Category:Companies listed on the Stock Exchange of Thailand]]\n[[Category:1972 establishments in Thailand]]\n[[Category:Instant noodle brands]]\n", "name_user": "Seligne", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFinancials", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thai_President_Foods"}
{"title_page": "Jesper Asselman", "text_new": "{{short description|Dutch cyclist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox cyclist\n| name           = Jesper Asselman\n| image          = Tongeren - Ronde van Limburg, 15 juni 2014 (F16).JPG\n| caption        = Asselman in 2014\n| fullname       = Jesper Asselman\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1990|3|12|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = [[Delft]], Netherlands\n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n| height         = 1.84 m\n| weight         = 69 kg\n| currentteam    = {{ct|MET}}\n| discipline     = Road\n| role           = Rider\n| ridertype      = Classics rider<ref name=wildestdreams />\n| amateuryears1  = \n| amateurteam1   = \n| proyears1      = 2009\u20132010\n| proteam1       = {{ct|RIJ|2009}}\n| proyears2      = 2011\n| proteam2       = {{ct|RB3|2011}}\n| proyears3      = 2012\n| proteam3       = {{ct|SSG|2012}}\n| proyears4      = 2013\u20132014\n| proteam4       = {{ct|MET|2013}}\n| proyears5      = 2015\u20132019\n| proteam5       = {{ct|ROO|2015}}\n| proyears6      = 2020\u2013\n| proteam6       = {{ct|MET|2020}}\n}}\n'''Jesper Asselman''' (born 12 March 1990) is a Dutch professional [[bicycle racing|racing cyclist]], who currently rides for [[UCI Continental team]] {{ct|MET}}.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.gelderlander.nl/sport-rivierenland/jesper-asselman-keert-terug-bij-metec~ad99a8da/|title=Jesper Asselman keert terug bij Metec|language=Dutch|trans-title=Jesper Asselman returns to Metec|date=22 November 2019|accessdate=28 December 2019|work=[[De Gelderlander]]|publisher=[[DPG Media]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uci.org/road/teams/TeamDetail/14107/1001725/257|title=Metec - TKH Continental Cyclingteam P / B Mantel|work=UCI.org|publisher=[[Union Cycliste Internationale]]|accessdate=16 April 2020|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200416205548/https://www.uci.org/road/teams/TeamDetail/14107/1001725/257|archivedate=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nPrior to rejoining {{ct|MET|2020|nolink=yes}} in 2020,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.fiets.nl/2018/10/05/lammertink-en-van-poppel-maken-roompot-charles-compleet/|title=Lammertink en Van Poppel maken Roompot-Charles compleet|first=Michael|last=Kerkhof|language=Dutch|trans-title=Lammertink and Van Poppel complete Roompot-Charles|work=Fiets|publisher=New Skool Media|date=5 October 2018|accessdate=24 January 2019}}</ref> Asselman rode for the {{ct|RNL|2019}} team during its five-year existence from 2015 to 2019. In the team's first year, Asselman rode in the [[2015 Eneco Tour|Eneco Tour]]; after spending two consecutive days in the breakaway and winning bonus seconds, he moved into the overall lead of the race.<ref name=wildestdreams>{{cite web |title=Asselman leads: 'Beyond my wildest dreams' |url=http://www.sport.be/enecotour/2015/en/nieuws/article.html?Article_ID=737546 |website=sport.be |publisher=[[Eneco Tour]] |accessdate=12 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Major results==\n{{Div col|colwidth=22em}}\n;2010\n: 7th [[Dwars door het Hageland]]\n;2011\n: 1st Stage 2b ([[Team time trial|TTT]]) [[Vuelta Ciclista a Le\u00f3n]]\n: 2nd [[Ronde van Overijssel]]\n: 5th [[Ronde van Midden-Nederland]]\n: 9th [[M\u00fcnsterland Giro]]\n;2012\n: 2nd [[Arno Wallaard Memorial]]\n: 7th [[Eschborn\u2013Frankfurt Under\u201323]]\n;2013\n: 1st [[File:MaillotHolanda.PNG|20px]] Scratch race, [[Dutch National Track Championships|National Track Championships]]\n: 5th [[Ronde van Midden-Nederland]]\n: 7th [[Ronde van Limburg (Belgium)|Ronde van Limburg]]\n;2014\n: 3rd Overall [[Olympia's Tour]]\n: 6th Overall [[World Ports Classic]]\n: 6th Overall [[Okolo Slovenska]]\n::1st Stage 1 ([[Team time trial|TTT]])\n: 6th [[Kernen Omloop Echt-Susteren]]\n: 7th [[Grote Prijs Stad Zottegem]]\n: 8th [[Grand Prix S\u00fcdk\u00e4rnten]]\n;2015\n: 4th [[Ronde van Drenthe]]\n: 4th [[Ronde van Limburg (Belgium)|Ronde van Limburg]]\n;2016\n: 1st [[Ronde van Drenthe]]\n;2017\n: 2nd [[Slag om Norg]]\n: 6th [[Le Samyn]]\n: 6th [[Dwars door West-Vlaanderen]]\n;2019\n: 1st Stage 1 [[2019 Tour de Yorkshire|Tour de Yorkshire]]\n: 9th [[2019 Le Samyn|Le Samyn]]\n: 9th [[Elfstedenronde]]\n: 10th [[Veenendaal\u2013Veenendaal Classic]]\n: 10th [[Antwerp Port Epic]]\n{{Div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{stack|{{Commons category|Jesper Asselman}}}}\n* {{Cycling Archives}}\n* {{CQ ranking}}\n* {{ProCyclingStats}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Asselman, Jesper}}\n[[Category:1990 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Dutch male cyclists]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Delft]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Dutch cyclist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox cyclist\n| name           = Jesper Asselman\n| image          = Tongeren - Ronde van Limburg, 15 juni 2014 (F16).JPG\n| caption        = Asselman in 2014\n| fullname       = Jesper Asselman\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1990|3|12|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = [[Delft]], Netherlands\n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n| height         = 1.84 m\n| weight         = 69 kg\n| currentteam    = {{ct|MET}}\n| discipline     = Road\n| role           = Rider\n| ridertype      = Classics rider<ref name=wildestdreams />\n| amateuryears1  = \n| amateurteam1   = \n| proyears1      = 2009\u20132010\n| proteam1       = {{ct|RIJ|2009}}\n| proyears2      = 2011\n| proteam2       = {{ct|RB3|2011}}\n| proyears3      = 2012\n| proteam3       = {{ct|SSG|2012}}\n| proyears4      = 2013\u20132014\n| proteam4       = {{ct|MET|2013}}\n| proyears5      = 2015\u20132019\n| proteam5       = {{ct|ROO|2015}}\n| proyears6      = 2020\u2013\n| proteam6       = {{ct|MET|2020}}\n}}\n'''Jesper Asselman''' (born 12 March 1990) is a Dutch professional [[bicycle racing|racing cyclist]], who currently rides for [[UCI Continental team]] {{ct|MET}}.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.gelderlander.nl/sport-rivierenland/jesper-asselman-keert-terug-bij-metec~ad99a8da/|title=Jesper Asselman keert terug bij Metec|language=Dutch|trans-title=Jesper Asselman returns to Metec|date=22 November 2019|accessdate=28 December 2019|work=[[De Gelderlander]]|publisher=[[DPG Media]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uci.org/road/teams/TeamDetail/14107/1001725/257|title=Metec - TKH Continental Cyclingteam P / B Mantel|work=UCI.org|publisher=[[Union Cycliste Internationale]]|accessdate=16 April 2020|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200416205548/https://www.uci.org/road/teams/TeamDetail/14107/1001725/257|archivedate=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nPrior to rejoining {{ct|MET|2020|nolink=yes}} in 2020,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.fiets.nl/2018/10/05/lammertink-en-van-poppel-maken-roompot-charles-compleet/|title=Lammertink en Van Poppel maken Roompot-Charles compleet|first=Michael|last=Kerkhof|language=Dutch|trans-title=Lammertink and Van Poppel complete Roompot-Charles|work=Fiets|publisher=New Skool Media|date=5 October 2018|accessdate=24 January 2019}}</ref> Asselman rode for the {{ct|RNL|2019}} team during its five-year existence from 2015 to 2019. In the team's first year, Asselman rode in the [[2015 Eneco Tour|Eneco Tour]]; after spending two consecutive days in the breakaway and winning bonus seconds, he moved into the overall lead of the race.<ref name=wildestdreams>{{cite web |title=Asselman leads: 'Beyond my wildest dreams' |url=http://www.sport.be/enecotour/2015/en/nieuws/article.html?Article_ID=737546 |website=sport.be |publisher=[[Eneco Tour]] |accessdate=12 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Major results==\n{{Div col|colwidth=22em}}\n;2010\n: 7th [[Dwars door het Hageland]]\n;2011\n: 1st Stage 2b ([[Team time trial|TTT]]) [[Vuelta Ciclista a Le\u00f3n]]\n: 2nd [[Ronde van Overijssel]]\n: 5th [[Ronde van Midden-Nederland]]\n: 9th [[M\u00fcnsterland Giro]]\n;2012\n: 2nd [[Arno Wallaard Memorial]]\n: 7th [[Eschborn\u2013Frankfurt Under\u201323]]\n;2013\n: 1st [[File:MaillotHolanda.PNG|20px]] Scratch race, [[Dutch National Track Championships|National Track Championships]]\n: 5th [[Ronde van Midden-Nederland]]\n: 7th [[Ronde van Limburg (Belgium)|Ronde van Limburg]]\n;2014\n: 3rd Overall [[Olympia's Tour]]\n: 6th Overall [[World Ports Classic]]\n: 6th Overall [[Okolo Slovenska]]\n::1st Stage 1 ([[Team time trial|TTT]])\n: 6th [[Kernen Omloop Echt-Susteren]]\n: 7th [[Grote Prijs Stad Zottegem]]\n: 8th [[Grand Prix S\u00fcdk\u00e4rnten]]\n;2015\n: 4th [[Ronde van Drenthe]]\n: 4th [[Ronde van Limburg (Belgium)|Ronde van Limburg]]\n;2016\n: 1st [[Ronde van Drenthe]]\n;2017\n: 2nd [[Slag om Norg]]\n: 6th [[Le Samyn]]\n: 6th [[Dwars door West-Vlaanderen]]\n;2019\n: 1st Stage 1 [[2019 Tour de Yorkshire|Tour de Yorkshire]]\n: 9th [[2019 Le Samyn|Le Samyn]]\n: 9th [[Elfstedenronde]]\n: 10th [[Veenendaal\u2013Veenendaal Classic]]\n: 10th [[Antwerp Port Epic]]\n{{Div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{stack|{{Commons category|Jesper Asselman}}}}\n* {{Cycling Archives}}\n* {{CQ ranking}}\n* {{ProCyclingStats}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Asselman, Jesper}}\n[[Category:1990 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Dutch male cyclists]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Delft]]\n", "name_user": "Lugnuts", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jesper_Asselman"}
{"title_page": "Free Media Movement", "text_new": "The '''Free Media Movement''' (FMM) is media freedom watchdog organization of Journalists from [[Sri Lanka]].\n\nIt evolved out of the standing committee of journalists, which was formed in late 1991. The standing committee was formed by a group of journalists and media personnel as a reaction to the then government of Sri Lanka to introduce a Media Commission.<ref name=IFEX>{{cite news | url= http://www.ifex.org/en/content/view/full/23236/ | title= Free Media Movement | date= 2007-06-20 | publisher= IFEX | accessdate= 2007-06-20 | archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20070214053412/http://www.ifex.org/en/content/view/full/23236/ | archive-date= 2007-02-14 | url-status= dead }}</ref>\n\nSince then '''FMM''' has been active in all areas relating to media freedom, defending the rights of journalists and media people. It also has called for reform of legislation,<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.asiamedia.ucla.edu/tsunami/article.asp?parentid=19345/ | title = Media group urges laws to permit access to information | date = 2007-06-20 | publisher = Asian Media | accessdate = 2007-06-20 }}{{Dead link|date=December 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> agitating against [[censorship]] and intimidation of media personnel and standing for broad principles of [[democracy|democratic]] and [[human rights]].<ref name=IFEX/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ahrchk.net/statements/mainfile.php/2003statement/81/| title= SRI LANKA: The Judiciary and Human Rights| date= 2007-06-20 | publisher = [[Asian Human Rights Commission]] | accessdate = 2007-06-20 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hrw.org/wr2k/Asia-08.htm/ |title=Human Rights Development in Sri Lanka |date=2007-06-20 |publisher=[[Human Rights Watch]] |accessdate=2007-06-20 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070617054544/http://www.hrw.org//wr2k/Asia-08.htm |archivedate=June 17, 2007 }}</ref>\n\nIt also has developed an extensive network of links with other media freedom and human rights groups locally and internationally.<ref name=IFEX/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.peacebrigades.org/lanka/slp9502.html |title=Interview with Sunandra Deshapriya of the Free Media Movement |date=2007-06-20 |publisher=Peace Brigades |accessdate=2007-06-20 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070207003211/http://www.peacebrigades.org/lanka/slp9502.html |archivedate=February 7, 2007 }}</ref>\n\nThe [[Sri Lanka]]n defense ministry alleged that FMM is a controversial<ref>{{cite news | url= http://www.defence.lk/new.asp?fname=20080523_09 | title= Police probe into alleged assault on journalist | date= 2008-05-23 | publisher= The official web site of the Ministry of Defence, Public Security, Law and Order of Sri Lanka | accessdate= 2008-05-23 | archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20120217095949/http://www.defence.lk/new.asp?fname=20080523_09 | archive-date= 2012-02-17 | url-status= dead }}</ref> organization. It has been alleged of unprofessionalism{{Citation needed|date=May 2008}} and partiality.{{Citation needed|date=May 2008}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.fmmsrilanka.lk Official website]\n*Media Reform Sri [http://www.mediareform.lk/ Lanka]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080501202905/http://www.humanrights-geneva.info/article.php3?id_article=1618 Media in Sri Lanka]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070928093900/http://www.ifj-asia.org/page/sri_lanka1.html Free Speech in Sri Lanka]\n\n[[Category:Sri Lankan journalism organisations]]\n[[Category:Freedom of expression organizations]]\n[[Category:Organizations established in 1991]]\n[[Category:1991 establishments in Sri Lanka]]\n\n\n{{journalism-stub}}\n", "text_old": "The '''Free Media Movement''' (FMM) is media freedom watchdog organization of Journalists from [[Sri Lanka]].\n\nIt evolved out of the standing committee of journalists, which was formed in late 1991. The standing committee was formed by a group of journalists and media personnel as a reaction to the then government of Sri Lanka to introduce a Media Commission.<ref name=IFEX>{{cite news | url= http://www.ifex.org/en/content/view/full/23236/ | title= Free Media Movement | date= 2007-06-20 | publisher= IFEX | accessdate= 2007-06-20 | archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20070214053412/http://www.ifex.org/en/content/view/full/23236/ | archive-date= 2007-02-14 | url-status= dead }}</ref>\n\nSince then '''FMM''' has been active in all areas relating to media freedom, defending the rights of journalists and media people. It also has called for reform of legislation,<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.asiamedia.ucla.edu/tsunami/article.asp?parentid=19345/ | title = Media group urges laws to permit access to information | date = 2007-06-20 | publisher = Asian Media | accessdate = 2007-06-20 }}{{Dead link|date=December 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> agitating against [[censorship]] and intimidation of media personnel and standing for broad principles of [[democracy|democratic]] and [[human rights]].<ref name=IFEX/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ahrchk.net/statements/mainfile.php/2003statement/81/| title= SRI LANKA: The Judiciary and Human Rights| date= 2007-06-20 | publisher = [[Asian Human Rights Commission]] | accessdate = 2007-06-20 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hrw.org/wr2k/Asia-08.htm/ |title=Human Rights Development in Sri Lanka |date=2007-06-20 |publisher=[[Human Rights Watch]] |accessdate=2007-06-20 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070617054544/http://www.hrw.org//wr2k/Asia-08.htm |archivedate=June 17, 2007 }}</ref>\n\nIt also has developed an extensive network of links with other media freedom and human rights groups locally and internationally.<ref name=IFEX/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.peacebrigades.org/lanka/slp9502.html |title=Interview with Sunandra Deshapriya of the Free Media Movement |date=2007-06-20 |publisher=Peace Brigades |accessdate=2007-06-20 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070207003211/http://www.peacebrigades.org/lanka/slp9502.html |archivedate=February 7, 2007 }}</ref>\n\nThe [[Sri Lanka]]n defense ministry alleged that FMM is a controversial<ref>{{cite news | url= http://www.defence.lk/new.asp?fname=20080523_09 | title= Police probe into alleged assault on journalist | date= 2008-05-23 | publisher= The official web site of the Ministry of Defence, Public Security, Law and Order of Sri Lanka | accessdate= 2008-05-23 | archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20120217095949/http://www.defence.lk/new.asp?fname=20080523_09 | archive-date= 2012-02-17 | url-status= dead }}</ref> organization. It has been alleged of unprofessionalism{{Citation needed|date=May 2008}} and partiality.{{Citation needed|date=May 2008}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.fmmsrilanka.lk Official website]\n*Media Reform in Sri Lanka www.mediareform.lk \n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080501202905/http://www.humanrights-geneva.info/article.php3?id_article=1618 Media in Sri Lanka]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070928093900/http://www.ifj-asia.org/page/sri_lanka1.html Free Speech in Sri Lanka]\n\n[[Category:Sri Lankan journalism organisations]]\n[[Category:Freedom of expression organizations]]\n[[Category:Organizations established in 1991]]\n[[Category:1991 establishments in Sri Lanka]]\n\n\n{{journalism-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Berni888", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add a new web site", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Free_Media_Movement"}
{"title_page": "Wild Rose (film)", "text_new": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = Wild Rose\n| image          = Wild Rose poster.jpg\n| border         = no\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Tom Harper (director)|Tom Harper]]\n| producer       = Faye Ward\n| writer         = Nicole Taylor\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Jessie Buckley]]\n* [[Sophie Okonedo]]\n* [[Julie Walters]]\n}}\n| music          = Jack Arnold\n| cinematography = George Steel\n| editing        = Mark Eckersley\n| production companies = {{Plainlist|\n* Fable Pictures\n* [[Creative Scotland]]\n* [[Film4 Productions]]\n* [[British Film Institute]]\n}}\n| distributor    = [[Entertainment One]]\n| released       = {{Film date|df=yes|2018|9|8|[[Toronto International Film Festival|TIFF]]|2019|4|12|United Kingdom}}\n| runtime        = 101 minutes\n| country        = United Kingdom\n| language       = English\n| budget         = \n| gross          = $7.1 million<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?page=main&id=wildrose.htm|title=Wild Rose|website=[[Box Office Mojo]]|accessdate=September 13, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Wild-Rose-(UK)-(2019)#tab=summary|title=Wild Rose|website=[[The Numbers (website)|The Numbers]]|accessdate=September 6, 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Wild Rose''''' is a 2018 British [[musical film|musical drama]] film directed by [[Tom Harper (director)|Tom Harper]] and starring [[Jessie Buckley]], [[Julie Walters]], [[Sophie Okonedo]], [[Jamie Sives]], [[Craig Parkinson]], [[James Harkness]], [[Janey Godley]], Daisy Littlefeld, Ryan Kerr, Adam Mitchell, and Nicole Kerr. The screenplay was written by Nicole Taylor.\n\nThe film had its world premiere at the [[Toronto International Film Festival]] on 8 September 2018 and was released on 12 April 2019, by [[Entertainment One]] in the United Kingdom.\n\nThe film received positive reviews, with Buckley earning a [[BAFTA Award for Best Actress in a Leading Role]] nomination for her performance.\n\n==Plot==\n\nRose-Lynn Harlan, an aspiring country singer and single mother of two from [[Glasgow]], is released after a year in prison for attempted drug smuggling. She learns that she has lost her longstanding job in the house band at Glasgow's Grand Ole Opry, as the manager refuses to employ a convicted criminal. Rose-Lynn's mother, Marion, who has been caring for Rose-Lynn's young children, encourages her to give up her music dream to focus on more practical careers and taking care of her family.\n\nRose-Lynn takes a cleaning job for Susannah's large house. Susannah's children overhear Rose-Lynn singing while she is cleaning and inform their mother, who confides that she is also a country music fan. Rose-Lynn asks Susannah for money to travel to [[Nashville]] and try to make it as a musician, but Susannah declines. However, she does get in contact with [[BBC Radio]] presenter, [[Bob Harris (radio presenter)|Bob Harris]], and sends him a recording of Rose-Lynn's singing; he offers to meet with her if she will come to London. Rose-Lynn appears before a judge to ask him to lift her curfew so she can travel, and he agrees. She travels by train to London and sits in on a live performance by the visiting [[Ashley McBryde]]. Harris encourages her to keep performing and figure out what she has to say so she can start writing her own songs.\n\nSusannah offers Rose-Lynn a performing gig at her upcoming house party, where she intends to ask her guests to contribute to Rose-Lynn's Nashville fund in lieu of gifts. Rose-Lynn asks Marion to watch the children in the week leading up to the party so she can rehearse, but Marion declines to cancel her holiday plans, so she is forced to shuttle her kids around to various friends who agree to watch them. The day before the performance, Susannah's husband pulls Rose-Lynn aside and says he knows about her conviction, threatening to tell his wife unless Rose-Lynn agrees to stay away from his children after her performance.\n\nRose-Lynn's son breaks his arm while playing unattended at home, and the doctors at the hospital say they cannot put a cast on until after Rose-Lynn's planned performance. Marion arrives to help and Rose-Lynn begs her to stay and watch her son so she can get to the party; Marion agrees but criticises her for neglecting her family. Rose-Lynn rushes to the party to perform, but breaks down and rushes off stage. She confesses to Susannah that she concealed her criminal record and that she had children, then leaves the party.\n\nRose-Lynn returns home and dedicates herself to her kids. Some time later, Marion presents her with a large sum of money she has saved, enough for her to travel to Nashville, having seen that Rose-Lynn has calmed down. Rose-Lynn tries to reject the money, but Marion expresses her regret about failing to accomplish her goals due to having kids. Rose-Lynn travels to Nashville and discovers how difficult it is to find gigs and get noticed. She sneaks on stage at the [[Ryman Auditorium]] during a backstage tour and sings an impromptu song to the empty building. A security guard approaches her afterward and offers to introduce her to a record producer, but Rose-Lynn decides to return to Glasgow, having realised that her future lies in her home town.\n\nOne year later, Rose-Lynn performs an original song at [[Celtic Connections]] titled \u201cGlasgow (No Place Like Home)\u201d and receives raucous applause.\n\n==Cast==\n{{cast listing|\n* [[Jessie Buckley]] as Rose-Lynn Harlan\n* [[Julie Walters]] as Marion\n* [[Sophie Okonedo]] as Susannah \n* [[Jamie Sives]] as Sam\n* [[Craig Parkinson]] as Alan\n* James Harkness as Elliot\n* [[Janey Godley]] as Barmaid\n* Daisy Littlefeld as Wynonna\n* Adam Mitchell as Lyle\n* Ryan Kerr as Rory \n* Nicole Kerr as Nell\n}}\nThe film also features cameo appearances from [[Kacey Musgraves]], [[Ashley McBryde]] and [[Bob Harris (radio presenter)|Bob Harris]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hallam |first1=Neil |title=Wild Rose Film Review - February 2019 |url=https://sixshootercountry.com/2019/02/25/wild-rose-movie-review/ |website=Six Shooter Country |accessdate=19 April 2019 |date=25 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\n[[File:Jessie Buckley, Tom Harper, and Nicole Taylor on Collider Video.jpg|right|thumb|(L-R) Nicole Taylor, Tom Harper, and Jessie Buckley discuss the film in 2018]]\nThe film had its world premiere at the [[Toronto International Film Festival]] on 8 September 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tiff.net/tiff/wild-rose/|title=Wild Rose|website=[[Toronto International Film Festival]]|accessdate=30 January 2019}}</ref> Shortly after, [[Neon (distributor)|NEON]] acquired [[film distribution|distribution]] rights to the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2018/film/markets-festivals/toronto-neon-nabs-wild-rose-1202934253/|title=Toronto: Neon Nabs \u2018Wild Rose\u2019|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|first=Brent|last=Lang|date=9 September 2018|accessdate=30 January 2019}}</ref> It  screened at the [[BFI London Film Festival]] on 15 October 2018<ref>{{cite web|url=https://whatson.bfi.org.uk/lff/Online/default.asp?BOparam::WScontent::loadArticle::permalink=wildrose&BOparam::WScontent::loadArticle::context_id=|title=Wild Rose|website=[[BFI Film Festival]]|accessdate=30 January 2019}}</ref> and   at [[South by Southwest]] in March 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/olivia-wilde-seth-rogen-matthew-mcconaughey-added-sxsw-film-fest-lineup-1176656|title=SXSW: Olivia Wilde, Seth Rogen, Charlize Theron and Matthew McConaughey to Premiere New Work|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|first=Gregg|last=Kilday|date=January 16, 2019|accessdate=January 30, 2019}}</ref> It was released in the United Kingdom on 12 April 2019, by [[Entertainment One]] and in the United States on 21 June 2019 by [[Neon (distributor)|NEON]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.firstshowing.net/2019/first-uk-trailer-for-country-singer-film-wild-rose-starring-jessie-buckley/|title=UK Trailer for Country Singer Film 'Wild Rose' Starring Jessie Buckley|website=First Showing|first=Alex|last=Billington|date=January 23, 2019|accessdate=January 30, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://birthmoviesdeath.com/2019/04/01/the-wild-rose-trailer-wants-to-pull-your-heartstrings|title=The WILD ROSE Trailer Wants To Pull Your Heartstrings|website=birthmoviesdeath.com|first=Evan|last=Saathoff|date=1 April 2019|accessdate=1 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Soundtrack==\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Wild Rose (Original Motion Picture Soundtrack)\n| type       = soundtrack\n| artist     = [[Jessie Buckley]]\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| released   = April 12, 2019\n| recorded   =\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = {{hlist|[[Soundtrack]]|[[country music|Country]]}}\n| length     = \n| label      = \n| producer   =\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = Wild Rose (Original Motion Picture Soundtrack)\n | type        = soundtrack\n | single1     = [[Country Girl (Primal Scream song)|Country Girl]]\n}}\n}}\nThe soundtrack features both original songs written exclusively for the film and covers of songs by established country artists such as [[Emmylou Harris]], [[Wynonna Judd]], [[Chris Stapleton]], [[Hank Snow]], folk artists [[John Prine]] and [[Patty Griffin]] as well as indie rock band [[Primal Scream]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://filmmusicreporter.com/2019/02/22/wild-rose-soundtrack-details/|title=\u2018Wild Rose\u2019 Soundtrack Details - Film Music Reporter|publisher=}}</ref> All songs are performed by singer [[Jessie Buckley]] with the exception of tracks 17, 18 and 19 (which are performed by The Bluegrass Smugglers) and track 20 (which is performed by Hillary Klug).  The album charted at No. 76 on the British album chart.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.officialcharts.com/charts/albums-chart/20190419/7502/ |title=Official Albums Chart Top 100: 19 April 2019 - 25 April 2019 |work=The Official Charts Company}}</ref>\n\n{{Anchor|Soundtrack}}\n\n{{tracklist\n| headline = ''Wild Rose (Original Motion Picture Soundtrack)''\n| extra_column = Original Artist\n\n| title1 = [[Country Girl (Primal Scream song)|Country Girl]]\n| extra1 = [[Primal Scream]]\n| writer1 = {{flatlist|\n*[[Martin Duffy (musician)|Martin Duffy]]\n*[[Bobby Gillespie]]\n*[[Andrew Innes]]\n*[[Mani (musician)|Gary Mounfield]]}}\n| length1 = 4:48\n\n| title2 = [[Traveller (Chris Stapleton album)|Outlaw State of Mind]]\n| extra2 = [[Chris Stapleton]]\n| writer2 = {{flatlist|\n*[[Ronnie Bowman]]\n*[[Jerry Salley]]\n*[[Chris Stapleton]]}}\n| length2 = 3:16\n\n| title3 = [[Born to Run (Emmylou Harris song)|Born to Run]]\n| extra3 = [[Emmylou Harris]]\n| writer3 = [[Paul Kennerley]]\n| length3 = 3:14\n\n| title4 = [[Her Story: Scenes from a Lifetime|Peace in This House]]\n| extra4 = [[Wynonna Judd]]\n| writer4 = {{flatlist|\n*Doug Gill\n*Angela Kaset}}\n| length4 = 4:41\n\n| title5 = [[I'm Moving On (Hank Snow song)|I'm Moving On]]\n| extra5 = [[Hank Snow]]\n| writer5 = [[Hank Snow]]\n| length5 = 2:16\n\n| title6 = Crying Over\n| extra6 = [[Patty Griffin]]\n| writer6 = [[Patty Griffin]]\n| length6 = 5:57\n\n| title7 = [[Angel from Montgomery]]\n| extra7 = [[John Prine]]\n| writer7 = [[John Prine]]\n| length7 = 4:05\n\n| title8 = Cigarette Row (5 O'Clock Freedom)\n| extra8 = N/A\n| writer8 =\n| length8 = 3:02\n\n| title9 = Alright to Be All Wrong (The Dreamer's Song)\n| extra9 = N/A\n| writer9 =\n| length9 = 3:04\n\n| title10 = [[Wynonna (album)|When I Reach the Place I'm Goin']]\n| extra10 = [[Wynonna Judd]]\n| writer10 = {{flatlist|\n*[[Emory Gordy Jr.]]\n*[[Joe Henry]]}}\n| length10 = 3:21\n\n| title11 = Glasgow (No Place Like Home)\n| extra11 = \n| writer11 = {{flatlist|\n*[[Mary Steenburgen]]\n*Caitlin Smith\n*Kate York}}\n| length11 = 4:13\n\n| title12 = [[Wrecking Ball (Emmylou Harris album)|Goin' Back to Harlan]]\n| extra12 = [[Emmylou Harris]]\n| writer12 = [[Anna McGarrigle]]\n| length12 = 4:29\n\n| title13 = Covered in Regret (Blue, Black and Red)\n| extra13 = N/A\n| writer13 =\n| length13 = 4:12\n\n| title14 = Robbing the Bank of Life (Stealing the Night)\n| extra14 = N/A\n| writer14 =\n| length14 = 2:21\n\n| title15 = That's the View from Here (Famous Folks Are Weird)\n| extra15 = N/A\n| writer15 =\n| length15 = 5:08\n\n| title16 = [[Boulder to Birmingham]]\n| extra16 = [[Emmylou Harris]]\n| writer16 = [[Emmylou Harris]]\n| length16 = 4:38\n\n| title17 = Euston Hustle\n| extra17 = N/A\n| writer17 = \n| length17 = 1:16\n\n| title18 = The Red Kitchen\n| extra18 = N/A\n| writer18 = \n| length18 = 0:56\n\n| title19 = The Beach\n| extra19 = N/A\n| writer19 = \n| length19 = 2:21\n\n| title20 = Le Petit Chat Gris\n| extra20 = N/A\n| writer20 = \n| length20 = 1:20\n\n| title21 = Glasgow (No Place Like Home) [live from the Old Fruit Market, Glasgow)\n| extra21 = N/A\n| writer21 =\n| length21 = 4:13\n}}\n\n==Reception==\n''Wild Rose'' received positive reviews from film critics. It holds a 94% approval rating on review aggregator website [[Rotten Tomatoes]], based on 161 reviews, with a [[Weighted arithmetic mean|weighted average]] of 7.78/10. The site's consensus reads: \"There's no shortage of star-is-born stories, but ''Wild Rose'' proves they can still be thoroughly entertaining -- and marks its own transcendent moment for lead Jessie Buckley\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/wild_rose_2019|title=Wild Rose|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=27 July 2019}}</ref> [[Metacritic]] reports a score of 80/100, based on 32 critics, indicating \"Generally favorable reviews\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/wild-rose|title=Wild Rose Reviews|website=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=28 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n\"Glasgow (No Place Like Home)\" from the movie's soundtrack won for Best Song at the [[25th Critics' Choice Awards]], tying with [[Elton John]] and [[Bernie Taupin]]'s \"[[(I'm Gonna) Love Me Again]]\" from ''[[Rocketman (film)|Rocketman]]''.<ref>https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/lists/2020-critics-choice-awards-nominations-list-full-1260595</ref><ref>https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/awards/8547864/rocketman-joker-music-wins-2020-critics-choice-awards</ref>\n\nJessie Buckley received a [[BAFTA]] nomination for [[BAFTA Award for Best Actress in a Leading Role|Best Actress]] for her role as Rose-Lynn.<ref>https://www.theguardian.com/film/2020/jan/07/the-full-list-of-nominations-for-the-baftas-2020</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official site|https://www.wildrosefilm.co.uk/home}}\n* {{IMDb title|5117428}}\n* {{Metacritic film|wild-rose}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|m/wild_rose_2019}}\n\n{{Tom Harper}}\n\n[[Category:2018 films]]\n[[Category:2010s musical drama films]]\n[[Category:British films]]\n[[Category:British musical drama films]]\n[[Category:Films about singers]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Tom Harper]]\n[[Category:Films set in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Entertainment One films]]\n[[Category:Film4 Productions films]]\n[[Category:Neon (distributor) films]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = Wild Rose\n| image          = Wild Rose poster.jpg\n| border         = no\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Tom Harper (director)|Tom Harper]]\n| producer       = Faye Ward\n| writer         = Nicole Taylor\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Jessie Buckley]]\n* [[Sophie Okonedo]]\n* [[Julie Walters]]\n}}\n| music          = Jack Arnold\n| cinematography = George Steel\n| editing        = Mark Eckersley\n| production companies = {{Plainlist|\n* Fable Pictures\n* [[Creative Scotland]]\n* [[Film4 Productions]]\n* [[British Film Institute]]\n}}\n| distributor    = [[Entertainment One]]\n| released       = {{Film date|df=yes|2018|9|8|[[Toronto International Film Festival|TIFF]]|2019|4|12|United Kingdom}}\n| runtime        = 101 minutes\n| country        = United Kingdom\n| language       = English\n| budget         = \n| gross          = $7.1 million<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?page=main&id=wildrose.htm|title=Wild Rose|website=[[Box Office Mojo]]|accessdate=September 13, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Wild-Rose-(UK)-(2019)#tab=summary|title=Wild Rose|website=[[The Numbers (website)|The Numbers]]|accessdate=September 6, 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Wild Rose''''' is a 2018 British [[musical film|musical drama]] film directed by [[Tom Harper (director)|Tom Harper]] and starring [[Jessie Buckley]], [[Julie Walters]], [[Sophie Okonedo]], [[Jamie Sives]], [[Craig Parkinson]], [[James Harkness]], [[Janey Godley]], Daisy Littlefeld, Ryan Kerr, Adam Mitchell, and Nicole Kerr. The screenplay was written by Nicole Taylor.\n\nThe film had its world premiere at the [[Toronto International Film Festival]] on 8 September 2018 and was released on 12 April 2019, by [[Entertainment One]] in the United Kingdom.\n\nThe film received positive reviews, with Buckley earning a [[BAFTA Award for Best Actress in a Leading Role]] nomination for her performance.\n\n==Plot==\n\nRose-Lynn Harlan, an aspiring country singer and single mother of two from [[Glasgow]], is released after a year in prison for attempted drug smuggling. She learns that she has lost her longstanding job in the house band at Glasgow's Grand Ole Opry, as the manager refuses to employ a convicted criminal. Rose-Lynn's mother, Marion, who has been caring for Rose-Lynn's young children, encourages her to give up her music dream to focus on more practical careers and taking care of her family.\n\nRose-Lynn takes a job as a housekeeper for Susannah. Susannah's children overhear Rose-Lynn singing while she is cleaning and inform their mother, who confides that she is also a country music fan. Rose-Lynn asks Susannah for money to travel to [[Nashville]] and try to make it as a musician, but Susannah declines. However, she does get in contact with [[BBC Radio]] presenter, [[Bob Harris (radio presenter)|Bob Harris]], and sends him a recording of Rose-Lynn's singing; he offers to meet with her if she will come to London. Rose-Lynn appears before a judge to ask him to lift her curfew so she can travel, and he agrees. She travels by train to London and sits in on a live performance by the visiting [[Ashley McBryde]]. Harris encourages her to keep performing and figure out what she has to say so she can start writing her own songs.\n\nSusannah offers Rose-Lynn a performing gig at her upcoming house party, where she intends to ask her guests to contribute to Rose-Lynn's Nashville fund in lieu of gifts. Rose-Lynn asks Marion to watch the children in the week leading up to the party so she can rehearse, but Marion declines to cancel her holiday plans, so she is forced to shuttle her kids around to various friends who agree to watch them. The day before the performance, Susannah's husband pulls Rose-Lynn aside and says he knows about her conviction, threatening to tell his wife unless Rose-Lynn agrees to stay away from his children after her performance.\n\nRose-Lynn's son breaks his arm while playing unattended at home, and the doctors at the hospital say they cannot put a cast on until after Rose-Lynn's planned performance. Marion arrives to help and Rose-Lynn begs her to stay and watch her son so she can get to the party; Marion agrees but criticises her for neglecting her family. Rose-Lynn rushes to the party to perform, but breaks down and rushes off stage. She confesses to Susannah that she concealed her criminal record and that she had children, then leaves the party.\n\nRose-Lynn returns home and dedicates herself to her kids. Some time later, Marion presents her with a large sum of money she has saved, enough for her to travel to Nashville, having seen that Rose-Lynn has calmed down. Rose-Lynn tries to reject the money, but Marion expresses her regret about failing to accomplish her goals due to having kids. Rose-Lynn travels to Nashville and discovers how difficult it is to find gigs and get noticed. She sneaks on stage at the [[Ryman Auditorium]] during a backstage tour and sings an impromptu song to the empty building. A security guard approaches her afterward and offers to introduce her to a record producer, but Rose-Lynn decides to return to Glasgow, having realised that her future lies in her home town.\n\nOne year later, Rose-Lynn performs an original song at [[Celtic Connections]] titled \u201cGlasgow (No Place Like Home)\u201d and receives raucous applause.\n\n==Cast==\n{{cast listing|\n* [[Jessie Buckley]] as Rose-Lynn Harlan\n* [[Julie Walters]] as Marion\n* [[Sophie Okonedo]] as Susannah \n* [[Jamie Sives]] as Sam\n* [[Craig Parkinson]] as Alan\n* James Harkness as Elliot\n* [[Janey Godley]] as Barmaid\n* Daisy Littlefeld as Wynonna\n* Adam Mitchell as Lyle\n* Ryan Kerr as Rory \n* Nicole Kerr as Nell\n}}\nThe film also features cameo appearances from [[Kacey Musgraves]], [[Ashley McBryde]] and [[Bob Harris (radio presenter)|Bob Harris]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hallam |first1=Neil |title=Wild Rose Film Review - February 2019 |url=https://sixshootercountry.com/2019/02/25/wild-rose-movie-review/ |website=Six Shooter Country |accessdate=19 April 2019 |date=25 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\n[[File:Jessie Buckley, Tom Harper, and Nicole Taylor on Collider Video.jpg|right|thumb|(L-R) Nicole Taylor, Tom Harper, and Jessie Buckley discuss the film in 2018]]\nThe film had its world premiere at the [[Toronto International Film Festival]] on 8 September 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tiff.net/tiff/wild-rose/|title=Wild Rose|website=[[Toronto International Film Festival]]|accessdate=30 January 2019}}</ref> Shortly after, [[Neon (distributor)|NEON]] acquired [[film distribution|distribution]] rights to the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2018/film/markets-festivals/toronto-neon-nabs-wild-rose-1202934253/|title=Toronto: Neon Nabs \u2018Wild Rose\u2019|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|first=Brent|last=Lang|date=9 September 2018|accessdate=30 January 2019}}</ref> It  screened at the [[BFI London Film Festival]] on 15 October 2018<ref>{{cite web|url=https://whatson.bfi.org.uk/lff/Online/default.asp?BOparam::WScontent::loadArticle::permalink=wildrose&BOparam::WScontent::loadArticle::context_id=|title=Wild Rose|website=[[BFI Film Festival]]|accessdate=30 January 2019}}</ref> and   at [[South by Southwest]] in March 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/olivia-wilde-seth-rogen-matthew-mcconaughey-added-sxsw-film-fest-lineup-1176656|title=SXSW: Olivia Wilde, Seth Rogen, Charlize Theron and Matthew McConaughey to Premiere New Work|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|first=Gregg|last=Kilday|date=January 16, 2019|accessdate=January 30, 2019}}</ref> It was released in the United Kingdom on 12 April 2019, by [[Entertainment One]] and in the United States on 21 June 2019 by [[Neon (distributor)|NEON]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.firstshowing.net/2019/first-uk-trailer-for-country-singer-film-wild-rose-starring-jessie-buckley/|title=UK Trailer for Country Singer Film 'Wild Rose' Starring Jessie Buckley|website=First Showing|first=Alex|last=Billington|date=January 23, 2019|accessdate=January 30, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://birthmoviesdeath.com/2019/04/01/the-wild-rose-trailer-wants-to-pull-your-heartstrings|title=The WILD ROSE Trailer Wants To Pull Your Heartstrings|website=birthmoviesdeath.com|first=Evan|last=Saathoff|date=1 April 2019|accessdate=1 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Soundtrack==\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Wild Rose (Original Motion Picture Soundtrack)\n| type       = soundtrack\n| artist     = [[Jessie Buckley]]\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| released   = April 12, 2019\n| recorded   =\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = {{hlist|[[Soundtrack]]|[[country music|Country]]}}\n| length     = \n| label      = \n| producer   =\n| prev_ti